Interview Questions
1. What is encapsulation in Java?
-->Encapsulation is the process of wrapping data (variables) and methods (behavior) together into a single unit called a class,
    and restricting direct access to the data using access modifiers.
    It is mainly achieved by:
    Declaring variables as private
    Providing public getter and setter methods
    
    Example:
    class Student {
        private String name;
    
        public void setName(String name) {
            this.name = name;
        }
    
        public String getName() {
            return name;
        }
    }



2. How is encapsulation different from abstraction?
-->
| Encapsulation                                        | Abstraction                                    |
| ---------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| Hides internal data                                  | Hides implementation details                   |
| Focuses on data security                             | Focuses on simplicity                          |
| Achieved using private variables and getters/setters | Achieved using abstract classes and interfaces |
| “How data is protected”                              | “What to show to user”                         |

Example:
Encapsulation → ATM protects account balance internally.
Abstraction → User only sees withdraw/deposit options.



3. Why is encapsulation important in object-oriented programming?
-->Encapsulation is important because it:
    Protects data from unauthorized access
    Improves security
    Increases maintainability
    Makes code reusable
    Allows controlled access to variables
    Reduces dependency between classes



4. How do you achieve encapsulation in Java?
-->Encapsulation is achieved by:

    Declaring class variables as private
    Providing public getter and setter methods
    
    Example:
    
    class Employee {
        private int salary;
    
        public int getSalary() {
            return salary;
        }
    
        public void setSalary(int salary) {
            if(salary > 0) {
                this.salary = salary;
            }
        }
    }



5. What are the benefits of using private variables in a class?
-->Benefits:
    Prevents direct modification
    Provides data security
    Allows validation before updating values
    Makes class behavior controlled
    Improves maintainability


6. Can you give a real time example of encapsulation in Java?
-->A bank account is a real-time example.
    
    Balance is hidden (private)
    Users access it through methods like:
    deposit()
    withdraw()
    getBalance()
    
    Example:
    
    class BankAccount {
        private double balance;
    
        public void deposit(double amount) {
            balance += amount;
        }
    
        public double getBalance() {
            return balance;
        }
    }




7. What is the role of getters and setters in encapsulation?
-->Getter → Used to read/access data
    Setter → Used to modify/update data
    
    They provide controlled access to private variables.
    
    Example:
    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
    
    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }



8. Is encapsulation possible without access modifiers?
-->No.
    Access modifiers are important for proper encapsulation.
    
    Without private, variables can be accessed directly from outside the class, which breaks data hiding.



